{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478692"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17536"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17536"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.1,0.34,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10226"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10226"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17536"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94649"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1259"},{"type":"tags","id":"3764"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46087"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of right leg pain and limping. He has become increasingly reluctant to walk. He has a fever of 38.5\u00b0C at home and appears irritable. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. He is tender over the proximal right tibia with localised warmth and swelling. He refuses to bear weight on the right leg. Hip examination is normal and he can flex and extend his knee.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal: white cell count 15.2 x 10^9/L (4.5-13.5), C-reactive protein 85 mg/L (\u003C5), erythrocyte sedimentation rate 65 mm/h (\u003C20).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Septic arthritis","Transient synovitis","Osteomyelitis","Legg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease","Slipped capital femoral epiphysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features highly suggestive of acute osteomyelitis, including localised bone pain, systemic symptoms, and significantly elevated inflammatory markers. \u003Cstrong\u003EOsteomyelitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, localised bone pain, and reduced weight bearing. The proximal tibia is a common site in children due to its rich blood supply. The key clinical finding is tenderness directly over the bone rather than joint involvement, supported by normal hip examination and preserved knee flexion and extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with joint pain, reduced range of motion, and systemic symptoms. While the presentation can be similar to osteomyelitis, the location of tenderness over the proximal tibia rather than within a joint, combined with normal hip examination and preserved knee movement, makes this less likely. Joint sepsis would typically cause significant restriction of joint movement due to pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient synovitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of acute hip pain and limp in children. However, it is typically self-limiting, associated with minimal systemic symptoms, and inflammatory markers are usually normal or only mildly elevated (ESR typically \u003C40 mm/h). The presence of high fever and markedly elevated inflammatory markers makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELegg-Calv\u00e9-Perthes disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an avascular necrosis of the femoral head that presents with chronic hip pain and limping. It typically has an insidious onset without systemic symptoms or elevated inflammatory markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESlipped capital femoral epiphysis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older children (10-15 years) and presents with hip or knee pain. It is not associated with fever or significantly elevated inflammatory markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe next steps in management would include blood cultures (before starting antibiotics), imaging (X-ray and MRI if available), and prompt initiation of appropriate intravenous antibiotics to cover common causative organisms including \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Elevated inflammatory markers (ESR \u003E40 mm/h) help differentiate septic arthritis/osteomyelitis from transient synovitis in a limping child.","Early osteomyelitis presents with localised bone pain, reduced weight bearing, and systemic symptoms.","Blood cultures should be obtained before starting antibiotics in suspected osteomyelitis."],"references":["Qi H, Zhu Z, Zhu D. Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate for Assisted Diagnosis of Pediatric Osteomyelitis: A Meta-Analysis. Ther Clin Risk Manag. 2023 Dec 7;19:1039-1049. doi: 10.2147/TCRM.S440996. PMID: 38089965; PMCID: PMC10712328.","Walter N, B\u00e4rtl S, Alt V, Rupp M. The Epidemiology of Osteomyelitis in Children. Children (Basel). 2021 Nov 3;8(11):1000. doi: 10.3390/children8111000. PMID: 34828711; PMCID: PMC8621985."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94649"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17536"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94649"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T18:48:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T18:51:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10226"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112619"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+